Imaginez une très longue page Web avec beaucoup de sections (p. ex., des spécifications sur une seule page HTML). Si l'utilisateur demande une section précise (p. ex. page.html#section7), que se passerait-il si le serveur web streamait d'abord cette section, puis les autres ?
Order of flow :
1. beginning of the HTML document until <body>
2. HTML for section 7
3. HTML for sections 1, 2, 3, etc.
The browser would then ensure to insert sections 1 to 6 *above* section 7 on the web page.
Does that sound clear? Could it be useful?
What I want to achieve is to get the rendering of the linked section (#section7) as fast as possible without having to reimplement anything with JavaScript. I just want to have a super long HTML document but with the fastest possible rendering of the linked sections. This should work with HTML.
The content could be streamed this way, and then the browser would inject each <contents> into its <div>.
<div id=sec1></div>
<div id=sec2></div>
etc.
<div id=sec7>section 7…</div>
<contents for=sec1>section 1…</contents>
<contents for=sec2>section 2…</contents>
etc.
This would be streamed out of order, but the browser would assemble the HTML document as if it was streamed in order.
@user22 You can reorganize the documents like this even without JS. You cannot use the hash part of the URL if you want the server to do something, but you can use query string parameters to tell the server which section you want to see first. To reorganize the parts, you have the choice between:
1. Using cascading stylesheets
2. Using a template with slots
@user23 Yes. The issue is that the visual order (what the user sees) does not match the DOM order. It might be useful to have an HTML feature that allows streaming out of order, and the browser would then reorganize the DOM content into the correct order.
But the approach with placements seems promising. I'll give it a try.
@user22 Oh, you want the browser to fix the DOM order?
@user23 Yes, that's the idea. Section 7 would be streamed first solely to allow the user to see it as soon as possible. It would be great if it could do this without affecting the DOM order, so that the browser can ensure the DOM order matches the visual order.
In other words, stream section 7 first, but make sure the final result (DOM and visual) is as if all sections had been streamed in order.
@user22 @user23 Check out PHOOOS without JS : https://github.com/niutech/phooos
